  <!-- WHAT IS A STOCK -->
  <div class="slide slide-foundation" data-week="0">
    <div class="f-eyebrow">// Before We Trade — Foundation</div>
    <h2>First: What is a stock?</h2>
    <div class="foundation-grid">
      <div class="f-box">
        <h3>A Company Needs Money to Grow</h3>
        <p>When a company wants to expand — hire people, build products, open new offices — it needs capital. One way to raise it is to sell small pieces of ownership in the company to the public. Each piece is called a <strong style="color:var(--text);">share of stock</strong>.</p>
        <div class="f-example">Apple needed capital → sold shares → people bought in → Apple grew</div>
      </div>
      <div class="f-box amber">
        <h3>You Buy a Share, You Own a Piece</h3>
        <p>When you buy one share of SOFI, you literally own a tiny slice of SoFi Technologies. If the company grows and becomes more valuable, your share becomes worth more. If it struggles, your share loses value. You are a part-owner.</p>
        <div class="f-example">1 share of SOFI at $4.80 = you own a piece of SoFi Technologies</div>
      </div>
      <div class="f-box">
        <h3>Stock Price Moves Every Second</h3>
        <p>The price of a stock changes constantly based on what buyers are willing to pay and what sellers are willing to accept. Good news, strong earnings, new products — price goes up. Bad news, weak outlook — price goes down. The market is a live auction, running 9:30am–4pm EST every weekday.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="f-box amber">
        <h3>Why Do People Buy Stocks?</h3>
        <p>Two reasons: <strong style="color:var(--text);">growth</strong> (the stock price rises over time, so their investment grows) and <strong style="color:var(--text);">income</strong> (some companies pay dividends — regular cash payments to shareholders). We're using stocks as the underlying asset for our options strategy.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- WHAT IS THE STOCK MARKET -->
  <div class="slide slide-foundation" data-week="0">
    <div class="f-eyebrow">// Before We Trade — Foundation</div>
    <h2>What is the stock market?</h2>
    <div class="foundation-grid">
      <div class="f-box">
        <h3>The Market is the Marketplace</h3>
        <p>The stock market is simply the organized system where buyers and sellers meet to trade shares. In the US, the two main exchanges are the <strong style="color:var(--text);">NYSE</strong> (New York Stock Exchange) and <strong style="color:var(--text);">Nasdaq</strong>. SOFI trades on Nasdaq.</p>
        <div class="f-example">Nasdaq: where SOFI, Apple, Google, Amazon all trade</div>
      </div>
      <div class="f-box amber">
        <h3>Thousands of Companies, One Platform</h3>
        <p>Over 5,000 companies are publicly traded in the US. When you hear "the market went up today," that means a major index like the <strong style="color:var(--text);">S&P 500</strong> — which tracks the 500 largest companies — rose in value. It's the scoreboard for the whole economy.</p>
        <div class="f-example">S&P 500 up 1% = most large US companies gained value today</div>
      </div>
      <div class="full-box">
        <p><strong style="color:var(--text);">The most important thing to understand:</strong> the stock market is not a casino. Over any 20-year period in American history, the stock market has gone up. Companies innovate, grow, and generate profit — and that profit flows to shareholders. Learning to participate in this system is how wealth gets built across generations. This is what we're here to learn.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="f-box">
        <h3>Market Hours</h3>
        <p>The US stock market is open Monday–Friday, 9:30am–4:00pm Eastern Time. Options can be placed during and slightly outside these hours depending on your broker. We trade during market hours only.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="f-box amber">
        <h3>Who Can Participate?</h3>
        <p>Anyone. All you need is a brokerage account, money to invest, and knowledge. There is no minimum age requirement with a custodial account. There is no zip code requirement. The market does not know your name, your background, or where you went to school. It only knows your trade.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

