  <!-- Vocab W1 -->
  <div class="slide slide-vocab" data-week="0">
    <div class="slide-sub">// Week 1 — Vocabulary</div>
    <div class="slide-heading">The Language of the Trade</div>
    <div class="vocab-list">
      <div class="vl-item">
        <div class="vl-term">Derivative</div>
        <div class="vl-def">A financial contract whose value is entirely derived from the price of an underlying asset. Options are derivatives of stocks.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vl-item">
        <div class="vl-term">Put Option</div>
        <div class="vl-def">Gives the buyer the <strong>Right</strong> to sell a stock at a set price. Gives the seller the <strong>Obligation</strong> to buy it at that price.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vl-item">
        <div class="vl-term">Premium</div>
        <div class="vl-def">Upfront cash the buyer pays the seller to enter the contract. The seller keeps this no matter what happens.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vl-item">
        <div class="vl-term">Cash Collateral</div>
        <div class="vl-def">Cash frozen in your account to guarantee you can fulfill your obligation. Formula: Strike Price × 100.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── SNEAKER WALKTHROUGH: 1 of 8 — The Setup ── -->
  <div class="slide slide-analogy" data-week="0">
    <div class="slide-sub" style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:0.7rem;letter-spacing:0.2em;color:var(--amber);text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:1rem;">// The Sneaker Trade · Step 1 of 8 — The Setup</div>
    <h2 style="font-family:'Syne',sans-serif;font-size:clamp(1.5rem,3.2vw,2.4rem);font-weight:800;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.25rem;">Every options trade starts with an underlying asset.</h2>
    <div class="analogy-box">
      A pair of SOFI-brand sneakers is trading on the resale market right now for <strong style="color:var(--amber);">$4.80 a pair</strong>. Someone owns 100 pairs of them.<br><br>
      That $4.80 market price is the <strong>underlying asset value</strong> — the real thing the contract is based on. In options trading, this is the stock price. Everything we do is tied to this number.
    </div>
    <div class="role-row" style="max-width:70vw;">
      <div class="role-box" style="border-top:2px solid var(--teal);">
        <div class="rl" style="color:var(--teal);">THE SNEAKER = THE STOCK</div>
        <div class="rd">The sneaker represents SOFI stock. The owner has 100 pairs — just like one options contract controls 100 shares.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="role-box" style="border-top:2px solid var(--amber);">
        <div class="rl" style="color:var(--amber);">$4.80 PRICE = THE STOCK PRICE</div>
        <div class="rd">$4.80 is what SOFI trades for right now. The owner paid $4.80 per pair. They're sitting on inventory and getting nervous about where the market is headed.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── SNEAKER WALKTHROUGH: 2 of 8 — The Players ── -->
  <div class="slide slide-analogy" data-week="0">
    <div class="slide-sub" style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:0.7rem;letter-spacing:0.2em;color:var(--amber);text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:1rem;">// The Sneaker Trade · Step 2 of 8 — The Players</div>
    <h2 style="font-family:'Syne',sans-serif;font-size:clamp(1.5rem,3.2vw,2.4rem);font-weight:800;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.25rem;">Two players. One contract. Very different positions.</h2>
    <div class="role-row" style="max-width:75vw;margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      <div class="role-box" style="padding:1.5rem;border-top:3px solid var(--teal);">
        <div class="rl" style="color:var(--teal);font-size:0.72rem;margin-bottom:0.5rem;">THE BUYER — The Sneaker Owner</div>
        <div class="rd" style="line-height:1.65;">Already owns 100 pairs of SOFI sneakers worth $4.80 each. Worried the resale market might crash. Wants <strong style="color:var(--text);">insurance</strong> — a guaranteed price they can sell at no matter what happens. They are <strong style="color:var(--text);">not trying to buy from you.</strong> They want the right to <em>sell to you</em>.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="role-box" style="padding:1.5rem;border-top:3px solid var(--amber);">
        <div class="rl" style="color:var(--amber);font-size:0.72rem;margin-bottom:0.5rem;">THE SELLER — The Store (US)</div>
        <div class="rd" style="line-height:1.65;">We run the store. We're willing to <strong style="color:var(--text);">buy their sneakers at a guaranteed price</strong> if the market drops — for a fee collected upfront. We are selling an insurance policy. We collect the premium whether they ever show up or not.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--amber);">→ We are always the store. We sell the insurance. We collect. We wait.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ── SNEAKER WALKTHROUGH: 3 of 8 — The Contract ── -->
  <div class="slide slide-analogy" data-week="0">
    <div class="slide-sub" style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:0.7rem;letter-spacing:0.2em;color:var(--amber);text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:1rem;">// The Sneaker Trade · Step 3 of 8 — The Contract Terms</div>
    <h2 style="font-family:'Syne',sans-serif;font-size:clamp(1.5rem,3.2vw,2.4rem);font-weight:800;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.25rem;">The owner walks in. Here's what they're asking for.</h2>
    <div class="analogy-box" style="max-width:72vw;">
      "I'll pay you <strong style="color:var(--amber);">$12 right now</strong> — cash, no refund — and in exchange, you give me a signed certificate that says I can walk in anytime over the next <strong style="color:var(--amber);">30 days</strong> and sell you my 100 pairs at <strong style="color:var(--amber);">$4.00 each</strong>, guaranteed."
    </div>
    <div class="role-row" style="max-width:72vw;">
      <div class="role-box">
        <div class="rl" style="color:var(--teal);">$12 CASH = THE PREMIUM</div>
        <div class="rd">The fee you collect upfront for agreeing to the deal. Yours immediately, forever, no matter what happens next.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="role-box">
        <div class="rl" style="color:var(--amber);">30 DAYS = EXPIRATION DATE</div>
        <div class="rd">The window the certificate is valid. After 30 days, the deal is dead. The certificate is worthless paper.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="role-box">
        <div class="rl" style="color:var(--green);">$4.00 = THE STRIKE PRICE</div>
        <div class="rd">The guaranteed buyback price. No matter what sneakers trade for on Day 30, you are obligated to buy at $4.00 per pair if they exercise.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── SNEAKER WALKTHROUGH: 4 of 8 — You Accept ── -->
  <div class="slide slide-analogy" data-week="0">
    <div class="slide-sub" style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:0.7rem;letter-spacing:0.2em;color:var(--amber);text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:1rem;">// The Sneaker Trade · Step 4 of 8 — You Accept the Deal</div>
    <h2 style="font-family:'Syne',sans-serif;font-size:clamp(1.5rem,3.2vw,2.4rem);font-weight:800;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.25rem;">You take the $12. Now you have one obligation.</h2>
    <div class="analogy-box" style="max-width:72vw;">
      You accept the $12 and sign the certificate. Then you open your register and set aside <strong style="color:var(--amber);">$400 in cash</strong> — 100 pairs × $4.00 — reserved and untouchable. If they walk in and exercise the certificate, you need that cash ready to buy their shoes. You're not holding inventory. You're holding the <strong style="color:var(--amber);">purchasing power</strong> to honor your word.
    </div>
    <div class="role-row" style="max-width:72vw;">
      <div class="role-box" style="border-top:3px solid var(--amber);">
        <div class="rl" style="color:var(--amber);">$12 COLLECTED = PREMIUM INCOME</div>
        <div class="rd">In your pocket immediately. This is your profit if the market holds and they never show up.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="role-box" style="border-top:3px solid var(--red);">
        <div class="rl" style="color:var(--red);">$400 IN REGISTER = CASH COLLATERAL</div>
        <div class="rd">In options: cash your broker freezes in your account. You can't spend it while the contract is open. This is exactly why the strategy is called "cash-secured" — the money to buy the shares is already there, waiting.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--muted);margin-top:1.25rem;">Day 1: $12 in pocket. $400 reserved. You're prepared for either outcome.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ── SNEAKER WALKTHROUGH: 4b — The $12 Is Credited, Not Locked ── -->
  <div class="slide slide-analogy" data-week="0">
    <div class="slide-sub" style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:0.7rem;letter-spacing:0.2em;color:var(--amber);text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:1rem;">// The Sneaker Trade · Step 4b — The $12 Is Credited, Not Locked</div>
    <h2 style="font-family:'Syne',sans-serif;font-size:clamp(1.5rem,3.2vw,2.4rem);font-weight:800;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.25rem;">The $12 is in your pocket. But the deal isn't over yet.</h2>
    <div class="analogy-box" style="max-width:78vw;">
      The moment the owner paid you and walked out the door, the $12 showed up in your register. You can see it. It feels like yours. <strong style="color:var(--amber);">But the certificate is still valid.</strong> They still have 30 days to come back.<br><br>
      Here's the catch: every day that passes, the value of that certificate changes based on what's happening in the sneaker market. If SOFI sneaker prices start dropping toward $4.00, other people in the market realize that certificate is becoming <em>more valuable</em> — they'd pay <em>more</em> than $12 for it now. Which means if you wanted to cancel the deal early, you'd have to buy that certificate back for <strong style="color:var(--red);">more than $12.</strong> That would be a loss.<br><br>
      On the other hand, if SOFI sneaker prices stay strong and move further away from $4.00, the certificate becomes <em>less valuable</em> every day — nobody wants to pay much for the right to sell at $4.00 when the market pays $4.80. Eventually it approaches worthless. You could buy it back for <strong style="color:var(--green);">pennies</strong>, or just wait for it to expire.
    </div>
    <div class="role-row" style="max-width:78vw;">
      <div class="role-box" style="border-top:3px solid var(--green);">
        <div class="rl" style="color:var(--green);">THE $12 BECOMES TRULY YOURS WHEN:</div>
        <div class="rd" style="line-height:1.7;">
          <strong style="color:var(--text);">1. The contract expires worthless.</strong> 30 days pass, SOFI stays above $4.00, the certificate is worthless paper. The $12 is now permanently locked in — you owe nothing.<br><br>
          <strong style="color:var(--text);">2. You buy the certificate back early (Buy to Close).</strong> You pay, say, $3 to cancel the deal before the 30 days are up. You locked in $9 of profit and removed all remaining risk.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="role-box" style="border-top:3px solid var(--red);">
        <div class="rl" style="color:var(--red);">THE $12 IS AT RISK WHEN:</div>
        <div class="rd" style="line-height:1.7;">
          The contract is still open and SOFI is falling toward your $4.00 strike. The certificate is gaining value in the market. If you had to cancel the deal right now, you'd pay more than $12 to do it.<br><br>
          <strong style="color:var(--text);">This is why you will see your position show a paper loss</strong> even though $12 already landed in your account. The position is marked to market in real time. Stay calm — it only matters what happens at expiration, or when you close.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--amber);margin-top:1.25rem;">The $12 is credited the moment you sell. It is locked the moment the contract closes — by expiration or by buying it back.</p>
  </div>

